'''Negative free bid''' is a [[contract bridge]] [[Glossary of contract bridge terms#treatment|treatment]] whereby a [[Glossary of contract bridge terms#freebid|free bid]] by responder over an opponent's overcall shows a long suit in a weak hand and is not forcing. This is in contrast with standard treatment, where a free bid can show unlimited values and is unconditionally forcing. The treatment is a relatively recent invention, and has become quite popular, especially in expert circles.
Negative free bids resolve relatively frequent situations where the responder holds a long suit with which he would like to compete for a partscore, but is deprived from bidding it by opponent's overcall.
==Example== {| class="wikitable" style="float:left; margin-right:10px;" !width="25%"|West||width="25%"|North||width="25%"|East||width="25%"|South |- align=center |||1{{diams}}||1{{spades}}||? |} For example, if South holds:&nbsp;{{BridgeHandInline|86|KJ10852|K6|532}}, partner opens 1{{Diams}} and East overcalls 1{{Spades}}, he couldn't bid 2{{Hearts}} in standard methods, as it would show 10+ [[Hand evaluation|high-card points]], and a [[negative double]] would be too off-shape. With NFB treatment in effect though, he can bid 2{{Hearts}} which the partner may pass (unless he has extra values and support, or an excellent suit of its own without tolerance for hearts). {{clear}} However, as a [[corollary]], negative free bids affect the scope of negative double; if the hand is suitable for "standard" forcing free bid (10-11+ points), a negative double has to be made first and the suit bid only in the next round. Thus, the negative double can be made with the following types of hand: *A weakish hand with unbid suits (unbid major) *A stronger hand with unbid suits *A strong (opening bid or more) one-suited hand. This can sometimes allow the opponents to [[preempt]] effectively. {| class="wikitable" style="float:left; margin-right:10px;" !width="25%"|West||width="25%"|North||width="25%"|East||width="25%"|South |- align=center |1{{Diams}}||1{{Hearts}}||Dbl||4{{Hearts}} |- align=center |?|| || || |} For example, West, holding: {{BridgeHandInline|KJ103|J8|AKQ104|J2}}, after this auction is in an awkward situation — he doesn't know whether partner has spades or not; whether South was bidding to make or to [[sacrifice (bridge)|sacrifice]] — is it correct to double, bid 4{{Spades}} or pass? {{clear}}
==See also== *[[Negative double]] *[[Support double]] *[[Takeout double]]
